      <hedline>
        <hl1>U.S. Team's Streak Intact</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Bill Pennington</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Pennington, Bill</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>American light welterweight boxer Ricardo Williams Jr advances to second round in boxing competition at Sydney Olympics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The American light welterweight Ricardo Williams Jr. didn't want to become the first United States boxer to falter and lose his first-round fight.</p>
        <p>Williams felt the pressure especially when he fell behind on points in the first round of his bout with Australian Henry Collins, who was supported by a small but boisterous home crowd at the boxing venue in Sydney's Darling Harbor.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The American light welterweight Ricardo Williams Jr. didn't want to become the first United States boxer to falter and lose his first-round fight.</p>
        <p>Williams felt the pressure especially when he fell behind on points in the first round of his bout with Australian Henry Collins, who was supported by a small but boisterous home crowd at the boxing venue in Sydney's Darling Harbor.</p>
        <p>But Williams, at 19 the youngest fighter on the American team, rallied and easily won the second and third rounds, building such a commanding lead (15 points) that the bout was stopped. The Americans have now won their nine first-round fights.</p>
        <p>Williams can't face the Cuban light welterweight Diogenes Luna Martinez until the semifinals, should Williams make it that far. And he can't face the reigning world champ Mahamadkadyz Abdullaev of Uzbekistan until the finals.</p>
        <p>Bill Pennington</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: ROUNDUP -- BOXING</p>
      </block>
